==English==
===Etymology===
{{G.}} [[Kriegsgefangen]].  Former POW Paul Gordon of Reading, Pennsylvania, claims to be the man who coined the term.  He was captured by the Germans after the B-17 in which he was a ball turret gunner was shot down over France on October 9, 1942; he spent the remainder of the war as a detainee in Stalag 17b, Krems, Austria.  Early in his captivity he was with a group of fellow POW's who were pondering what to call themselves, since the German word "Kriegsgefangen" (war-prisoner) was too cumbersome.  According to Paul, he said, "Heck, we'll just be Kriegies," and the name stuck.

